[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The CLIP method trains a pair of models contrastively.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] One model takes in a piece of text as input and outputs a single vector representing its semantic content.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The other model takes in an image and similarly outputs a single vector representing its visual content.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The models are trained so that the vectors corresponding to semantically similar text-image pairs are close together in the shared vector space, while those corresponding to dissimilar pairs are far apart.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] To train a pair of CLIP models, one would start by preparing a large dataset of image-caption pairs.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] During training, the models are presented with batches of N image-caption pairs.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] Two vectors are considered "similar" if their dot product is large.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] For each image, the similarity scores with the N texts are converted by a softmax into a probability distribution over which text is the matching one.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] Cross-entropy is then computed against the one-hot target that assigns probability 1 to the correct text; the same calculation is also performed in the text-to-image direction.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The parameter $T>0$ is the temperature, which is parameterized in the original CLIP model as $T=e^{-\tau }$ where $\tau \in \mathbb {R}$ is a learned parameter.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] For example, Sigmoid CLIP (SigLIP) proposes the following loss function: $L={\frac {1}{N}}\sum _{i,j\in 1:N}f((2\delta _{i,j}-1)(e^{\tau }w_{i}\cdot v_{j}+b))$ where $f(x)=\ln(1+e^{-x})$ is the negative log sigmoid loss, and the Dirac delta symbol $\delta _{i,j}$ is 1 if $i=j$ else 0.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] While the original model was developed by OpenAI, subsequent models have been trained by other organizations as well.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The image encoding models used in CLIP are typically vision transformers (ViT).
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The naming convention for these models often reflects the specific ViT architecture used.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] For instance, "ViT-L/14" means a "vision transformer large" (compared to other models in the same series) with a patch size of 14, meaning that the image is divided into 14-by-14 pixel patches before being processed by the transformer.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The size indicator ranges from B, L, H, G (base, large, huge, giant), in that order.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] Other than ViT, the image model is typically a convolutional neural network, such as ResNet (in the original series by OpenAI), or ConvNeXt (in the OpenCLIP model series by LAION).
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] Since the output vectors of the image model and the text model must have exactly the same length, both the image model and the text model have fixed-length vector outputs, which in the original report is called "embedding dimension".
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] For example, in the original OpenAI model, the ResNet models have embedding dimensions ranging from 512 to 1024, and for the ViTs, from 512 to 768.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] Its implementation of ViT was the same as the original one, with one modification: after position embeddings are added to the initial patch embeddings, there is a LayerNorm.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] ALIGN a model with similar capabilities, trained by researchers from Google used EfficientNet, a kind of convolutional neural network.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The text encoding models used in CLIP are typically transformers.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] In the original OpenAI report, they reported using a Transformer (63M-parameter, 12-layer, 512-wide, 8 attention heads) with lower-cased byte pair encoding (BPE) with 49152 vocabulary size.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] Context length was capped at 76 for efficiency.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] Like GPT, it was decoder-only, with only causally-masked self-attention.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] Like BERT, the text sequence is bracketed by two special tokens `[SOS]` and `[EOS]` ("start of sequence" and "end of sequence").
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] Take the activations of the highest layer of the transformer on the `[EOS]`, apply LayerNorm, then a final linear map.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] This is the text encoding of the input sequence.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The final linear map has output dimension equal to the embedding dimension of whatever image encoder it is paired with.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] These models all had context length 77 and vocabulary size 49408.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The CLIP models released by OpenAI were trained on a dataset called "WebImageText" (WIT) containing 400 million pairs of images and their corresponding captions scraped from the internet.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The total number of words in this dataset is similar in scale to the WebText dataset used for training GPT-2, which contains about 40 gigabytes of text data.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The dataset contains 500,000 text-queries, with up to 20,000 (image, text) pairs per query.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The text-queries were generated by starting with all words occurring at least 100 times in English Wikipedia, then extended by bigrams with high mutual information, names of all Wikipedia articles above a certain search volume, and WordNet synsets.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The dataset is private and has not been released to the public, and there is no further information on it.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The rationale was that these are the mean and standard deviations of the images in the WebImageText dataset, so this preprocessing step roughly whitens the image tensor.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] ALIGN used over one billion image-text pairs, obtained by extracting images and their alt-tags from online crawling.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The method was described as similar to how the Conceptual Captions dataset was constructed, but instead of complex filtering, they only applied a frequency-based filtering.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] Later models trained by other organizations had published datasets.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] For example, LAION trained OpenCLIP with published datasets LAION-400M, LAION-2B, and DataComp-1B.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] In the original OpenAI CLIP report, they reported training 5 ResNet and 3 ViT (ViT-B/32, ViT-B/16, ViT-L/14).
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The largest ResNet model took 18 days to train on 592 V100 GPUs.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The largest ViT model took 12 days on 256 V100 GPUs.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] All ViT models were trained on 224×224 image resolution.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The ViT-L/14 was then boosted to 336×336 resolution by FixRes, resulting in a model.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] They found this was the best-performing model.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] In the OpenCLIP series, the ViT-L/14 model was trained on 384 A100 GPUs on the LAION-2B dataset, for 160 epochs for a total of 32B samples seen.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] CLIP's cross-modal retrieval enables the alignment of visual and textual data in a shared latent space, allowing users to retrieve images based on text descriptions and vice versa, without the need for explicit image annotations.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] In **text-to-image retrieval**, users input descriptive text, and CLIP retrieves images with matching embeddings.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] In **image-to-text retrieval**, images are used to find related text content.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] CLIP’s ability to connect visual and textual data has found applications in multimedia search, content discovery, and recommendation systems.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] CLIP can perform zero-shot image classification tasks.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] This is achieved by prompting the text encoder with class names and selecting the class whose embedding is closest to the image embedding.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] For example, to classify an image, they compared the embedding of the image with the embedding of the text "A photo of a {class}.", and the {class} that results in the highest dot product is outputted.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] CLIP has been used as a component in multimodal learning.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] For example, during the training of Google DeepMind's Flamingo (2022), the authors trained a CLIP pair, with BERT as the text encoder and NormalizerFree ResNet F6 as the image encoder.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The image encoder of the CLIP pair was taken with parameters frozen and the text encoder was discarded.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The frozen image encoder was then combined with a frozen Chinchilla language model, by finetuning with some further parameters that connect the two frozen models.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] During SSL, the model learns in two steps.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] First, the task is solved based on an auxiliary or pretext classification task using pseudo-labels, which help to initialize the model parameters.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Next, the actual task is performed with supervised or unsupervised learning.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Self-supervised learning has produced promising results in recent years, and has found practical application in fields such as audio processing, and is being used by Facebook and others for speech recognition.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Pseudo-labels are automatically generated labels that a model assigns to unlabeled data based on its own predictions.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] They are widely used in self-supervised and semi-supervised learning, where ground-truth annotations are limited or unavailable.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] By treating predicted labels as surrogate ground truth, learning algorithms can make use of large quantities of unlabeled data in the training process.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Pseudo-labeling also plays an important role in systems that must adapt to concept drift, where the statistical properties of the data change over time.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] In these scenarios, the model may detect that an incoming instance deviates from previously learned behavior.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] The system then generates a classification result for that instance, and this predicted class is used as a pseudo-label for updating or retraining model components that are becoming outdated.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] This approach enables continuous adaptation in dynamic environments without requiring manual annotation.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] In many adaptive learning pipelines, pseudo-labels are chosen when the classifier produces sufficiently confident predictions, reducing the risk of propagating errors.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] These pseudo-labeled instances are then incorporated into training to refresh or evolve the model's understanding of emerging data patterns, particularly when existing components show signs of “aging” due to drift or distributional shifts.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] This strategy reduces reliance on manual labeling while helping maintain long-term model performance.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Autoassociative self-supervised learning is a specific category of self-supervised learning where a neural network is trained to reproduce or reconstruct its own input data.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] In other words, the model is tasked with learning a representation of the data that captures its essential features or structure, allowing it to regenerate the original input.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] The term "autoassociative" comes from the fact that the model is essentially associating the input data with itself.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] This is often achieved using autoencoders, which are a type of neural network architecture used for representation learning.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Autoencoders consist of an *encoder* network that maps the input data to a lower-dimensional representation (latent space), and a *decoder* network that reconstructs the input from this representation.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] The training process involves presenting the model with input data and requiring it to reconstruct the same data as closely as possible.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] The loss function used during training typically penalizes the difference between the original input and the reconstructed output (e.g. mean squared error).
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] By minimizing this reconstruction error, the autoencoder learns a meaningful representation of the data in its latent space.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] For a binary classification task, training data can be divided into positive examples and negative examples.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Positive examples are those that match the target.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] For example, if training a classifier to identify birds, the positive training data would include images that contain birds.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Negative examples would be images that do not.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Contrastive self-supervised learning uses both positive and negative examples.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] The loss function in contrastive learning is used to minimize the distance between positive sample pairs, while maximizing the distance between negative sample pairs.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] An early example uses a pair of 1-dimensional convolutional neural networks to process a pair of images and maximize their agreement.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Contrastive Language-Image Pre-training (CLIP) allows joint pretraining of a text encoder and an image encoder, such that a matching image-text pair have image encoding vector and text encoding vector that span a small angle (having a large cosine similarity).
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] InfoNCE (Noise-Contrastive Estimation) is a method to optimize two models jointly, based on Noise Contrastive Estimation (NCE).
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Non-contrastive self-supervised learning (NCSSL) uses only positive examples.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Counterintuitively, NCSSL converges on a useful local minimum rather than reaching a trivial solution, with zero loss.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] For the example of binary classification, it would trivially learn to classify each example as positive.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Effective NCSSL requires an extra predictor on the online side that does not back-propagate on the target side.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] A major class of self-supervised learning moves beyond contrastive pairs, instead maximizing the agreement between views while preventing collapse through statistical constraints.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Rooted in Deep Canonical Correlation Analysis (Deep CCA), this approach includes Joint-Embedding Architectures (JEA) like Barlow Twins and VICReg, which enforce covariance constraints to learn invariant representations without negative sampling.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Deep Latent Variable Path Modelling (DLVPM) generalizes this to multimodal systems, using path models to enforce correlation and orthogonality across diverse data types.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] In 2022 Yann LeCun introduced Joint-Embedding Predictive Architectures (JEPA) as a step towards decision making, reasoning, and autonomous human intelligence in machines, including self-improvement through autonomous learning.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Founded in representation learning, LeCun included the concept of a “world model” in JEPA which aims to enable machines to replicate human intellect by providing machines with a concept for the world in which they exist.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Unlike autoencoders, JEPAs operate entirely in latent space, avoiding pixel-level noise to focus on semantic structure.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Rather than just learning invariance, JEPAs learn by predicting masked latent representations from visible context.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] JEPA has been applied to domains such as image analysis, audio processing, and motion in images and video.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] SSL belongs to supervised learning methods insofar as the goal is to generate a classified output from the input.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] At the same time, however, it does not require the explicit use of labeled input-output pairs.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Instead, correlations, metadata embedded in the data, or domain knowledge present in the input are implicitly and autonomously extracted from the data.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] These supervisory signals, extracted from the data, can then be used for training.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] SSL is similar to unsupervised learning in that it does not require labels in the sample data.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Unlike unsupervised learning, however, learning is not done using inherent data structures.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Semi-supervised learning combines supervised and unsupervised learning, requiring only a small portion of the learning data be labeled.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] In transfer learning, a model designed for one task is reused on a different task.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Training an autoencoder intrinsically constitutes a self-supervised process, because the output pattern needs to become an optimal reconstruction of the input pattern itself.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] However, in current jargon, the term 'self-supervised' often refers to tasks based on a pretext-task training setup.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] This involves the (human) design of such pretext task(s), unlike the case of fully self-contained autoencoder training.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] In reinforcement learning, self-supervising learning from a combination of losses can create abstract representations where only the most important information about the state are kept in a compressed way.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Self-supervised learning is particularly suitable for speech recognition.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] For example, Facebook developed *wav2vec*, a self-supervised algorithm, to perform speech recognition using two deep convolutional neural networks that build on each other.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Google's Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers (BERT) model is used to better understand the context of search queries.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] OpenAI's GPT-3 is an autoregressive language model that can be used in language processing.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] It can be used to translate texts or answer questions, among other things.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] The Yarowsky algorithm is an example of self-supervised learning in natural language processing.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] From a small number of labeled examples, it learns to predict which word sense of a polysemous word is being used at a given point in text.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] DirectPred is a NCSSL that directly sets the predictor weights instead of learning it via typical gradient descent.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Self-GenomeNet is an example of self-supervised learning in genomics.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] SelfAPR is an example of self-supervised learning applied to automated program repair, where a neural model is trained on perturbations of a previous version of the program under repair and uses test execution diagnostics to synthesize patches.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Self-supervised learning continues to gain prominence as a new approach across diverse fields.
[src:contrastive-learning/contrastive-learning] Its ability to leverage unlabeled data effectively opens new possibilities for advancement in machine learning, especially in data-driven application domains.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] In machine learning (ML), **feature learning** or **representation learning** is a set of techniques that allow a system to automatically discover the representations needed for feature detection or classification from raw data.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] This replaces manual feature engineering and allows a machine to both learn the features and use them to perform a specific task.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Feature learning is motivated by the fact that ML tasks such as classification often require input that is mathematically and computationally convenient to process.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] However, real-world data, such as image, video, and sensor data, have not yielded to attempts to algorithmically define specific features.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] An alternative is to discover such features or representations through examination, without relying on explicit algorithms.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Supervised feature learning is learning features from labeled data.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The data label allows the system to compute an error term, the degree to which the system fails to produce the label, which can then be used as feedback to correct the learning process (reduce/minimize the error).
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Dictionary learning develops a set (dictionary) of representative elements from the input data such that each data point can be represented as a weighted sum of the representative elements.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The dictionary elements and the weights may be found by minimizing the average representation error (over the input data), together with *L1* regularization on the weights to enable sparsity (i.e., the representation of each data point has only a few nonzero weights).
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Supervised dictionary learning exploits both the structure underlying the input data and the labels for optimizing the dictionary elements.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] For example, this supervised dictionary learning technique applies dictionary learning on classification problems by jointly optimizing the dictionary elements, weights for representing data points, and parameters of the classifier based on the input data.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Neural networks are a family of learning algorithms that use a "network" consisting of multiple layers of inter-connected nodes.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] It is inspired by the animal nervous system, where the nodes are viewed as neurons and edges are viewed as synapses.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Each edge has an associated weight, and the network defines computational rules for passing input data from the network's input layer to the output layer.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] A network function associated with a neural network characterizes the relationship between input and output layers, which is parameterized by the weights.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] With appropriately defined network functions, various learning tasks can be performed by minimizing a cost function over the network function (weights).
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Multilayer neural networks can be used to perform feature learning, since they learn a representation of their input at the hidden layer(s) which is subsequently used for classification or regression at the output layer.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The most popular network architecture of this type is Siamese networks.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Unsupervised feature learning is learning features from unlabeled data.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The goal of unsupervised feature learning is often to discover low-dimensional features that capture some structure underlying the high-dimensional input data.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] When the feature learning is performed in an unsupervised way, it enables a form of semisupervised learning where features learned from an unlabeled dataset are then employed to improve performance in a supervised setting with labeled data.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Several approaches are introduced in the following.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] K-means clustering can be used to group an unlabeled set of inputs into *k* clusters, and then use the centroids of these clusters to produce features.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] These features can be produced in several ways.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The simplest is to add *k* binary features to each sample, where each feature *j* has value one iff the *j*th centroid learned by *k*-means is the closest to the sample under consideration.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] It is also possible to use the distances to the clusters as features, perhaps after transforming them through a radial basis function (a technique that has been used to train RBF networks).
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Coates and Ng note that certain variants of *k*-means behave similarly to sparse coding algorithms.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] In a comparative evaluation of unsupervised feature learning methods, Coates, Lee and Ng found that *k*-means clustering with an appropriate transformation outperforms the more recently invented auto-encoders and RBMs on an image classification task.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] *K*-means also improves performance in the domain of NLP, specifically for named-entity recognition; there, it competes with Brown clustering, as well as with distributed word representations (also known as neural word embeddings).
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Principal component analysis (PCA) is often used for dimension reduction.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Equivalently, these singular vectors are the eigenvectors corresponding to the *p* largest eigenvalues of the sample covariance matrix of the input vectors.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] These *p* singular vectors are the feature vectors learned from the input data, and they represent directions along which the data has the largest variations.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] PCA is a linear feature learning approach since the *p* singular vectors are linear functions of the data matrix.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The singular vectors can be generated via a simple algorithm with *p* iterations.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] In the *i*th iteration, the projection of the data matrix on the *(i-1)*th eigenvector is subtracted, and the *i*th singular vector is found as the right singular vector corresponding to the largest singular of the residual data matrix.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] First, it assumes that the directions with large variance are of most interest, which may not be the case.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] PCA only relies on orthogonal transformations of the original data, and it exploits only the first- and second-order moments of the data, which may not well characterize the data distribution.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Furthermore, PCA can effectively reduce dimension only when the input data vectors are correlated (which results in a few dominant eigenvalues).
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Local linear embedding (LLE) is a nonlinear learning approach for generating low-dimensional neighbor-preserving representations from (unlabeled) high-dimension input.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The approach was proposed by Roweis and Saul (2000).
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The general idea of LLE is to reconstruct the original high-dimensional data using lower-dimensional points while maintaining some geometric properties of the neighborhoods in the original data set.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The second step is for "dimension reduction," by looking for vectors in a lower-dimensional space that minimizes the representation error using the optimized weights in the first step.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Note that in the first step, the weights are optimized with fixed data, which can be solved as a least squares problem.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] In the second step, lower-dimensional points are optimized with fixed weights, which can be solved via sparse eigenvalue decomposition.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The reconstruction weights obtained in the first step capture the "intrinsic geometric properties" of a neighborhood in the input data.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] It is assumed that original data lie on a smooth lower-dimensional manifold, and the "intrinsic geometric properties" captured by the weights of the original data are also expected to be on the manifold.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] This is why the same weights are used in the second step of LLE.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Compared with PCA, LLE is more powerful in exploiting the underlying data structure.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Independent component analysis (ICA) is a technique for forming a data representation using a weighted sum of independent non-Gaussian components.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The assumption of non-Gaussian is imposed since the weights cannot be uniquely determined when all the components follow Gaussian distribution.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Unsupervised dictionary learning does not utilize data labels and exploits the structure underlying the data for optimizing dictionary elements.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] An example of unsupervised dictionary learning is sparse coding, which aims to learn basis functions (dictionary elements) for data representation from unlabeled input data.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Sparse coding can be applied to learn overcomplete dictionaries, where the number of dictionary elements is larger than the dimension of the input data.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Aharon et al. proposed algorithm K-SVD for learning a dictionary of elements that enables sparse representation.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The hierarchical architecture of the biological neural system inspires deep learning architectures for feature learning by stacking multiple layers of learning nodes.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] These architectures are often designed based on the assumption of distributed representation: observed data is generated by the interactions of many different factors on multiple levels.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] In a deep learning architecture, the output of each intermediate layer can be viewed as a representation of the original input data.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Each level uses the representation produced by the previous, lower level as input, and produces new representations as output, which are then fed to higher levels.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The input at the bottom layer is raw data, and the output of the final, highest layer is the final low-dimensional feature or representation.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Restricted Boltzmann machines (RBMs) are often used as a building block for multilayer learning architectures.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] An RBM can be represented by an undirected bipartite graph consisting of a group of binary hidden variables, a group of visible variables, and edges connecting the hidden and visible nodes.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] It is a special case of the more general Boltzmann machines with the constraint of no intra-node connections.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Each edge in an RBM is associated with a weight.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The weights together with the connections define an energy function, based on which a joint distribution of visible and hidden nodes can be devised.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Based on the topology of the RBM, the hidden (visible) variables are independent, conditioned on the visible (hidden) variables.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Such conditional independence facilitates computations.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] An RBM can be viewed as a single layer architecture for unsupervised feature learning.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] In particular, the visible variables correspond to input data, and the hidden variables correspond to feature detectors.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The weights can be trained by maximizing the probability of visible variables using Hinton's contrastive divergence (CD) algorithm.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] In general, training RBMs by solving the maximization problem tends to result in non-sparse representations.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Sparse RBM was proposed to enable sparse representations.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The idea is to add a regularization term in the objective function of data likelihood, which penalizes the deviation of the expected hidden variables from a small constant p .
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] RBMs have also been used to obtain *disentangled* representations of data, where interesting features map to separate hidden units.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] An autoencoder consisting of an encoder and a decoder is a paradigm for deep learning architectures.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] An example is provided by Hinton and Salakhutdinov where the encoder uses raw data (e.g., image) as input and produces feature or representation as output and the decoder uses the extracted feature from the encoder as input and reconstructs the original input raw data as output.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The encoder and decoder are constructed by stacking multiple layers of RBMs.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The parameters involved in the architecture were originally trained in a greedy layer-by-layer manner: after one layer of feature detectors is learned, they are fed up as visible variables for training the corresponding RBM.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Current approaches typically apply end-to-end training with stochastic gradient descent methods.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Training can be repeated until some stopping criteria are satisfied.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Self-supervised representation learning is learning features by training on the structure of unlabeled data rather than relying on explicit labels for an information signal.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] This approach has enabled the combined use of deep neural network architectures and larger unlabeled datasets to produce deep feature representations.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Training tasks typically fall under the classes of either contrastive, generative or both.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Contrastive representation learning trains representations for associated data pairs, called positive samples, to be aligned, while pairs with no relation, called negative samples, are contrasted.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] A larger portion of negative samples is typically necessary in order to prevent catastrophic collapse, which is when all inputs are mapped to the same representation.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Generative representation learning tasks the model with producing the correct data to either match a restricted input or reconstruct the full input from a lower dimensional representation.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] A common setup for self-supervised representation learning of a certain data type (e.g. text, image, audio, video) is to pretrain the model using large datasets of general context, unlabeled data.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Depending on the context, the result of this is either a set of representations for common data segments (e.g. words) which new data can be broken into, or a neural network able to convert each new data point (e.g. image) into a set of lower dimensional features.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] In either case, the output representations can then be used as an initialization in many different problem settings where labeled data may be limited.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Specialization of the model to specific tasks is typically done with supervised learning, either by fine-tuning the model / representations with the labels as the signal, or freezing the representations and training an additional model which takes them as an input.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Many self-supervised training schemes have been developed for use in representation learning of various modalities, often first showing successful application in text or image before being transferred to other data types.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Word2vec is a word embedding technique which learns to represent words through self-supervision over each word and its neighboring words in a sliding window across a large corpus of text.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The model has two possible training schemes to produce word vector representations, one generative and one contrastive.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The first is word prediction given each of the neighboring words as an input.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The second is training on the representation similarity for neighboring words and representation dissimilarity for random pairs of words.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] A limitation of word2vec is that only the pairwise co-occurrence structure of the data is used, and not the ordering or entire set of context words.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] More recent transformer-based representation learning approaches attempt to solve this with word prediction tasks.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] GPTs pretrain on next word prediction using prior input words as context, whereas BERT masks random tokens in order to provide bidirectional context.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Other self-supervised techniques extend word embeddings by finding representations for larger text structures such as sentences or paragraphs in the input data.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Doc2vec extends the generative training approach in word2vec by adding an additional input to the word prediction task based on the paragraph it is within, and is therefore intended to represent paragraph level context.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The domain of image representation learning has employed many different self-supervised training techniques, including transformation, inpainting, patch discrimination and clustering.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Many other self-supervised methods use siamese networks, which generate different views of the image through various augmentations that are then aligned to have similar representations.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] The challenge is avoiding collapsing solutions where the model encodes all images to the same representation.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] SimCLR is a contrastive approach which uses negative examples in order to generate image representations with a ResNet CNN.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Bootstrap Your Own Latent (BYOL) removes the need for negative samples by encoding one of the views with a slow moving average of the model parameters as they are being modified during training.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Another approach is to maximize mutual information, a measure of similarity, between the representations of associated structures within the graph.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] An example is Deep Graph Infomax, which uses contrastive self-supervision based on mutual information between the representation of a "patch" around each node, and a summary representation of the entire graph.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Negative samples are obtained by pairing the graph representation with either representations from another graph in a multigraph training setting, or corrupted patch representations in single graph training.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] With analogous results in masked prediction and clustering, video representation learning approaches are often similar to image techniques but must utilize the temporal sequence of video frames as an additional learned structure.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Examples include VCP, which masks video clips and trains to choose the correct one given a set of clip options, and Xu et al., who train a 3D-CNN to identify the original order given a shuffled set of video clips.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Self-supervised representation techniques have also been applied to many audio data formats, particularly for speech processing.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Wav2vec 2.0 discretizes the audio waveform into timesteps via temporal convolutions, and then trains a transformer on masked prediction of random timesteps using a contrastive loss.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] This is similar to the BERT language model, except as in many SSL approaches to video, the model chooses among a set of options rather than over the entire word vocabulary.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Self-supervised learning has also been used to develop joint representations of multiple data types.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Approaches usually rely on some natural or human-derived association between the modalities as an implicit label, for instance video clips of animals or objects with characteristic sounds, or captions written to describe images.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] CLIP produces a joint image-text representation space by training to align image and text encodings from a large dataset of image-caption pairs using a contrastive loss.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Multimodal representation models are typically unable to assume direct correspondence of representations in the different modalities, since the precise alignment can often be noisy or ambiguous.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] For example, the text "dog" could be paired with many different pictures of dogs, and correspondingly a picture of a dog could be captioned with varying degrees of specificity.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] This limitation means that downstream tasks may require an additional generative mapping network between modalities to achieve optimal performance, such as in DALLE-2 for text to image generation.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Dynamic representation learning methods generate latent embeddings for dynamic systems such as dynamic networks.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Since particular distance functions are invariant under particular linear transformations, different sets of embedding vectors can actually represent the same/similar information.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Therefore, for a dynamic system, a temporal difference in its embeddings may be explained by misalignment of embeddings due to arbitrary transformations and/or actual changes in the system.
[src:contrastive-learning/representation-learning] Therefore, generally speaking, temporal embeddings learned via dynamic representation learning methods should be inspected for any spurious changes and be aligned before consequent dynamic analyses.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Conceptually, unsupervised learning divides into the aspects of data, training, algorithm, and downstream applications.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Typically, the dataset is harvested cheaply "in the wild", such as massive text corpus obtained by web crawling, with only minor filtering (such as Common Crawl).
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] This compares favorably to supervised learning, where the dataset (such as the ImageNet1000) is typically constructed manually, which is much more expensive.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] There are algorithms designed specifically for unsupervised learning, such as clustering algorithms like k-means, dimensionality reduction techniques like principal component analysis (PCA), Boltzmann machine learning, and autoencoders.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] After the rise of deep learning, most large-scale unsupervised learning has been done by training general-purpose neural network architectures by gradient descent, adapted to performing unsupervised learning by designing an appropriate training procedure.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Sometimes a trained model can be used as-is, but more often they are modified for downstream applications.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] For example, the generative pretraining method trains a model to generate a textual dataset, before finetuning it for other applications, such as text classification.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] As another example, autoencoders are trained to produce good features, which can then be used as a module for other models, such as in a latent diffusion model.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Tasks are often categorized as discriminative (recognition) or generative (imagination).
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Often but not always, discriminative tasks use supervised methods and generative tasks use unsupervised (see Venn diagram); however, the separation is very hazy.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] For example, object recognition favors supervised learning but unsupervised learning can also cluster objects into groups.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Furthermore, as progress marches onward, some tasks employ both methods, and some tasks swing from one to another.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] For example, image recognition started off as heavily supervised, but became hybrid by employing unsupervised pre-training, and then moved towards supervision again with the advent of dropout, ReLU, and adaptive learning rates.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] A typical generative task is as follows.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] At each step, a datapoint is sampled from the dataset, and part of the data is removed, and the model must infer the removed part.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] This is particularly clear for the denoising autoencoders and BERT.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] During the learning phase, an unsupervised network tries to mimic the data it is given and uses the error in its mimicked output to correct itself (i.e. correct its weights and biases).
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Sometimes the error is expressed as a low probability that the erroneous output occurs, or it might be expressed as an unstable high energy state in the network.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] An energy function is a macroscopic measure of a network's activation state.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] In Boltzmann machines, it plays the role of the Cost function.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] This analogy with physics is inspired by Ludwig Boltzmann's analysis of a gas' macroscopic energy from the microscopic probabilities of particle motion $p\propto e^{-E/kT}$ , where k is the Boltzmann constant and T is temperature.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] In the RBM network the relation is $p=e^{-E}/Z$ , where p and E vary over every possible activation pattern and $\textstyle {Z=\sum _{\scriptscriptstyle {\text{All Patterns}}}e^{-E({\text{pattern}})}}$ .
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] To be more precise, $p(a)=e^{-E(a)}/Z$ , where a is an activation pattern of all neurons (visible and hidden).
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Hence, some early neural networks bear the name Boltzmann Machine.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Paul Smolensky calls $-E\,$ the *Harmony*.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] A network seeks low energy which is high Harmony.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] This table shows connection diagrams of various unsupervised networks, the details of which will be given in the section Comparison of Networks.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Circles are neurons and edges between them are connection weights.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] As network design changes, features are added on to enable new capabilities or removed to make learning faster.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] For instance, neurons change between deterministic (Hopfield) and stochastic (Boltzmann) to allow robust output, weights are removed within a layer (RBM) to hasten learning, or connections are allowed to become asymmetric (Helmholtz).
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Of the networks bearing people's names, only Hopfield worked directly with neural networks.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Boltzmann and Helmholtz came before artificial neural networks, but their work in physics and physiology inspired the analytical methods that were used.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Here, we highlight some characteristics of select networks.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] The details of each are given in the comparison table below.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Ferromagnetism inspired Hopfield networks.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] A neuron corresponds to an iron domain with binary magnetic moments Up and Down, and neural connections correspond to the domain's influence on each other.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Symmetric connections enable a global energy formulation.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] During inference the network updates each state using the standard activation step function.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Symmetric weights and the right energy functions guarantees convergence to a stable activation pattern.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Asymmetric weights are difficult to analyze.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Hopfield nets are used as Content Addressable Memories (CAM).
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] as follows: suppose a binary neuron fires with the Bernoulli probability p(1) = 1/3 and rests with p(0) = 2/3.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] , which in this case is the step function thresholded at 2/3.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Introduced by Radford Neal in 1992, this network applies ideas from probabilistic graphical models to neural networks.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] A key difference is that nodes in graphical models have pre-assigned meanings, whereas Belief Net neurons' features are determined after training.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] The network is a sparsely connected directed acyclic graph composed of binary stochastic neurons.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] 's are activations from an unbiased sample of the posterior distribution and this is problematic due to the Explaining Away problem raised by Judea Perl.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] uses a surrogate posterior and blatantly disregard this complexity.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Introduced by Hinton, this network is a hybrid of RBM and Sigmoid Belief Network.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] The top 2 layers is an RBM and the second layer downwards form a sigmoid belief network.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] method and then throw away the recognition weights below the top RBM.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] As of 2009, 3-4 layers seems to be the optimal depth.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] These are early inspirations for the Variational Auto Encoders.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Its 2 networks combined into one—forward weights operates recognition and backward weights implements imagination.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] It is perhaps the first network to do both.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Helmholtz did not work in machine learning but he inspired the view of "statistical inference engine whose function is to infer probable causes of sensory input".
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] the stochastic binary neuron outputs a probability that its state is 0 or 1.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] The data input is normally not considered a layer, but in the Helmholtz machine generation mode, the data layer receives input from the middle layer and has separate weights for this purpose, so it is considered a layer.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] These are inspired by Helmholtz machines and combines probability network with neural networks.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] An Autoencoder is a 3-layer CAM network, where the middle layer is supposed to be some internal representation of input patterns.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] The weights are named phi & theta rather than W and V as in Helmholtz—a cosmetic difference.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] These 2 networks here can be fully connected, or use another NN scheme.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] The classical example of unsupervised learning in the study of neural networks is Donald Hebb's principle, that is, neurons that fire together wire together.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] In Hebbian learning, the connection is reinforced irrespective of an error, but is exclusively a function of the coincidence between action potentials between the two neurons.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] A similar version that modifies synaptic weights takes into account the time between the action potentials (spike-timing-dependent plasticity or STDP).
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Hebbian Learning has been hypothesized to underlie a range of cognitive functions, such as pattern recognition and experiential learning.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Among neural network models, the self-organizing map (SOM) and adaptive resonance theory (ART) are commonly used in unsupervised learning algorithms.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] The SOM is a topographic organization in which nearby locations in the map represent inputs with similar properties.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] The ART model allows the number of clusters to vary with problem size and lets the user control the degree of similarity between members of the same clusters by means of a user-defined constant called the vigilance parameter.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] ART networks are used for many pattern recognition tasks, such as automatic target recognition and seismic signal processing.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Two of the main methods used in unsupervised learning are principal component and cluster analysis.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Cluster analysis is used in unsupervised learning to group, or segment, datasets with shared attributes in order to extrapolate algorithmic relationships.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Cluster analysis is a branch of machine learning that groups the data that has not been labelled, classified or categorized.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Instead of responding to feedback, cluster analysis identifies commonalities in the data and reacts based on the presence or absence of such commonalities in each new piece of data.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] This approach helps detect anomalous data points that do not fit into either group.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] A central application of unsupervised learning is in the field of density estimation in statistics, though unsupervised learning encompasses many other domains involving summarizing and explaining data features.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] It can be contrasted with supervised learning by saying that whereas supervised learning intends to infer a conditional probability distribution conditioned on the label of input data; unsupervised learning intends to infer an a priori probability distribution .
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Some of the most common algorithms used in unsupervised learning include: (1) Clustering, (2) Anomaly detection, (3) Approaches for learning latent variable models.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] One of the statistical approaches for unsupervised learning is the method of moments.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] In the method of moments, the unknown parameters (of interest) in the model are related to the moments of one or more random variables, and thus, these unknown parameters can be estimated given the moments.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] The moments are usually estimated from samples empirically.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] The basic moments are first and second order moments.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] For a random vector, the first order moment is the mean vector, and the second order moment is the covariance matrix (when the mean is zero).
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Higher order moments are usually represented using tensors which are the generalization of matrices to higher orders as multi-dimensional arrays.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] In particular, the method of moments is shown to be effective in learning the parameters of latent variable models.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] Latent variable models are statistical models where in addition to the observed variables, a set of latent variables also exists which is not observed.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] A highly practical example of latent variable models in machine learning is the topic modeling which is a statistical model for generating the words (observed variables) in the document based on the topic (latent variable) of the document.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] In the topic modeling, the words in the document are generated according to different statistical parameters when the topic of the document is changed.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] It is shown that method of moments (tensor decomposition techniques) consistently recover the parameters of a large class of latent variable models under some assumptions.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] The Expectation–maximization algorithm (EM) is also one of the most practical methods for learning latent variable models.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] However, it can get stuck in local optima, and it is not guaranteed that the algorithm will converge to the true unknown parameters of the model.
[src:contrastive-learning/unsupervised-learning] In contrast, for the method of moments, the global convergence is guaranteed under some conditions.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] In natural language processing, a **word embedding** is a representation of a word.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Typically, the representation is a real-valued vector that encodes the meaning of the word in such a way that the words that are closer in the vector space are expected to be similar in meaning.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Word embeddings can be obtained using language modeling and feature learning techniques, where words or phrases from the vocabulary are mapped to vectors of real numbers.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Methods to generate this mapping include neural networks, dimensionality reduction on the word co-occurrence matrix, probabilistic models, explainable knowledge base method, and explicit representation in terms of the context in which words appear.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Word and phrase embeddings, when used as the underlying input representation, have been shown to boost the performance in NLP tasks such as syntactic parsing and sentiment analysis.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] In distributional semantics, a quantitative methodological approach for understanding meaning in observed language, word embeddings or semantic feature space models have been used as a knowledge representation for some time.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Such models aim to quantify and categorize semantic similarities between linguistic items based on their distributional properties in large samples of language data.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] The underlying idea that "a word is characterized by the company it keeps" was proposed in a 1957 article by John Rupert Firth, but also has roots in the contemporaneous work on search systems and in cognitive psychology.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] The first generation of semantic space models is the vector space model for information retrieval.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Such vector space models for words and their distributional data implemented in their simplest form results in a very sparse vector space of high dimensionality (cf. curse of dimensionality).
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Reducing the number of dimensions using linear algebraic methods such as singular value decomposition then led to the introduction of latent semantic analysis in the late 1980s and the random indexing approach for collecting word co-occurrence contexts.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] In 2000, Bengio et al. provided in a series of papers titled "Neural probabilistic language models" to reduce the high dimensionality of word representations in contexts by "learning a distributed representation for words".
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] A study published in NeurIPS (NIPS) 2002 introduced the use of both word and document embeddings applying the method of kernel CCA to bilingual (and multi-lingual) corpora, also providing an early example of self-supervised learning of word embeddings.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Word embeddings come in two different styles, one in which words are expressed as vectors of co-occurring words, and another in which words are expressed as vectors of linguistic contexts in which the words occur; these different styles are studied in Lavelli et al., 2004.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Roweis and Saul published in *Science* how to use "locally linear embedding" (LLE) to discover representations of high dimensional data structures.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Most new word embedding techniques after about 2005 rely on a neural network architecture instead of more probabilistic and algebraic models, after foundational work done by Yoshua Bengio and colleagues.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] The approach has been adopted by many research groups after theoretical advances in 2010 had been made on the quality of vectors and the training speed of the model, as well as after hardware advances allowed for a broader parameter space to be explored profitably.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] In 2013, a team at Google led by Tomas Mikolov created word2vec, a word embedding toolkit that can train vector space models faster than previous approaches.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] The word2vec approach has been widely used in experimentation and was instrumental in raising interest for word embeddings as a technology, moving the research strand out of specialised research into broader experimentation and eventually paving the way for practical application.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Historically, one of the main limitations of static word embeddings or word vector space models is that words with multiple meanings are conflated into a single representation (a single vector in the semantic space).
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] In other words, polysemy and homonymy are not handled properly.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] For example, in the sentence "The club I tried yesterday was great!", it is not clear if the term *club* is related to the word sense of a *club sandwich*, *clubhouse*, *golf club*, or any other sense that *club* might have.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] The necessity to accommodate multiple meanings per word in different vectors (multi-sense embeddings) is the motivation for several contributions in NLP to split single-sense embeddings into multi-sense ones.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Most approaches that produce multi-sense embeddings can be divided into two main categories for their word sense representation, i.e., unsupervised and knowledge-based.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Based on word2vec skip-gram, Multi-Sense Skip-Gram (MSSG) performs word-sense discrimination and embedding simultaneously, improving its training time, while assuming a specific number of senses for each word.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] In the Non-Parametric Multi-Sense Skip-Gram (NP-MSSG) this number can vary depending on each word.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Once the words are disambiguated, they can be used in a standard word embeddings technique, so multi-sense embeddings are produced.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] MSSA architecture allows the disambiguation and annotation process to be performed recurrently in a self-improving manner.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] The use of multi-sense embeddings is known to improve performance in several NLP tasks, such as part-of-speech tagging, semantic relation identification, semantic relatedness, named entity recognition and sentiment analysis.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] As of the late 2010s, contextually-meaningful embeddings such as ELMo and BERT have been developed.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Unlike static word embeddings, these embeddings are at the token-level, in that each occurrence of a word has its own embedding.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] These embeddings better reflect the multi-sense nature of words, because occurrences of a word in similar contexts are situated in similar regions of BERT's embedding space.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Word embeddings for *n-*grams in biological sequences (e.g.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] DNA, RNA, and proteins) for bioinformatics applications have been proposed by Asgari and Mofrad.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Named bio-vectors (BioVec) to refer to biological sequences in general with protein-vectors (ProtVec) for proteins (amino-acid sequences) and gene-vectors (GeneVec) for gene sequences, this representation can be widely used in applications of deep learning in proteomics and genomics.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] The results presented by Asgari and Mofrad suggest that BioVectors can characterize biological sequences in terms of biochemical and biophysical interpretations of the underlying patterns.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Word embeddings with applications in game design have been proposed by Rabii and Cook as a way to discover emergent gameplay using logs of gameplay data.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] The process requires transcribing actions that occur during a game within a formal language and then using the resulting text to create word embeddings.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] The results presented by Rabii and Cook suggest that the resulting vectors can capture expert knowledge about games like chess that are not explicitly stated in the game's rules.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] The idea has been extended to embeddings of entire sentences or even documents, e.g. in the form of the thought vectors concept.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] In 2015, some researchers suggested "skip-thought vectors" as a means to improve the quality of machine translation.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] A more recent and popular approach for representing sentences is Sentence-BERT, or SentenceTransformers, which modifies pre-trained BERT with the use of siamese and triplet network structures.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Software for training and using word embeddings includes Tomáš Mikolov's Word2vec, Stanford University's GloVe, GN-GloVe, Flair embeddings, AllenNLP's ELMo, BERT, fastText, Gensim, Indra, and Deeplearning4j.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Principal Component Analysis (PCA), Uniform manifold approximation and projection (UMAP), and T-Distributed Stochastic Neighbour Embedding (t-SNE) are used to reduce the dimensionality of word vector spaces and visualize word embeddings and clusters.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] For instance, the fastText is also used to calculate word embeddings for text corpora in Sketch Engine that are available online.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Word embeddings may contain the biases and stereotypes contained in the trained dataset, as Bolukbasi et al. points out in the 2016 paper "Man is to Computer Programmer as Woman is to Homemaker?
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] For example, one of the analogies generated using the aforementioned word embedding is "man is to computer programmer as woman is to homemaker".
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Research done by Jieyu Zhao et al. shows that the applications of these trained word embeddings without careful oversight likely perpetuates existing bias in society, which is introduced through unaltered training data.
[src:contrastive-learning/word-embedding] Furthermore, word embeddings can even amplify these biases.
